2022 - some core memories ✨

This year has definitely been one of the most challenging but best years of my life so far. It felt like a roller coaster during the spring while finishing up D1, and then the excitement continued during the summer when we moved into Sim lab and started practicing our skills in lab everyday. In the fall we had lectures that aligned with what we were doing in lab that day and it really helped explain the reason behind why we use certain materials/specific dimensions and concepts of dentistry.  This fall semester was probably my favorite because we had a lot of rotations in the clinic and interacting with patients is the aspect I like most about dentistry. I feel so thankful to be making progress in my career and life in general, and I can’t wait to see you all in dental school or in your professions as well! I think sometimes in college or D1 it’s easy to feel exhausted and lost as to why you’re constantly studying so much biology, chemistry, organic chemistry, etc. but it’s important to remember that yes, those are the foundations BUT you will eventually get to the fun stuff which is learning all the amazing things you can do as a dentist, which will ultimately enable you to make huge impacts on those around you. 
If no one has told you lately, you’re doing great and you WILL make it! I’m proud of you. Keep doing your best and everything will work out with time 🤍

a day in my life: winter break edition

1st stop: volunteering in the morning: 
📍Allan Saxe Dental Clinic
•this is one of my favorite places to volunteer in Arlington, tx. It is located right across the street from my undergrad college (UT Arlington) so I would go here in the mornings before class and in between classes to get my shadowing + volunteering hours in! I learned everything I know about dental assisting here. How to take x-rays, assist properly, chart, sterilize instruments, etc. definitely recommend this place to volunteer if you need hours and are in the DFW area. Note: only open from 8am-noon. 

2nd stop: dental office collecting teeth 🦷
📍Lakewood dental studios 
Tomorrow we start the second semester of D2 and I needed to collect extracted teeth for our endo projects. I asked on my story if anyone knew where I could get some and thankfully Dr. Leisa swiped up on my story and gave me some! I toured the office and was in awe at how beautiful it was. I love seeing other dentists achieve their dreams because it inspires me to keep working towards it too! 🦷 while there I also asked for advice on topics I have been curious about! don’t be afraid to go out and network, it’s always helpful to get advice from people who have already done it! 

3rd stop: lunch + coffee shop
📍Carrollton , tx
I ended my day out by grabbing lunch & going to a coffee shop to edit content + work on some paperwork. 

I’m curious what y’all have been to and I hope everyone has a great start to the semester! 🤍

studying at coffee shops >>>>
📚💻👩‍💻🦷☕️

Tips for lack of study motivation: 

💻 I recommend getting up and going to places where others are being productive when you can’t find motivation! It really helps to move spots and be surrounded by people who are focused on their work and passionate about what they are working on. This could be a coffee shop, a library, school, or even a friends house. Anywhere that you will feel a bit of encouragement to keep studying 🤍

💻 take small breaks during your studies. There are a lot of free timer websites that can track when you should study and how often you can take breaks. I use the Pomodoro technique and use a free online website to time myself (I work 40 minutes and break for 5 minutes but you can adjust this to what fits you) 

💻 reward yourself after you complete your tasks. This gives you something to look forward to and helps you stay on track. This could be scheduling a fun time with your friends after you finish your work or just taking some “me” time and having a self-care night. This will help you associate your studies with a feeling of accomplishment and reward once they’re complete. 

It’s not easy and sometimes we feel burnt out, but it’s important to seek out new methods and even help from others to get us back on track ✨🤍

Good luck with your studies everyone 📚✨ YOU GOT THIS!

✨Don’t be hard on yourself. Just do your best!✨

I loved this audio and wanted to share this with you guys. A lot of times we strive for perfection but we forget it’s our first time doing a lot of these things! Maybe you’re busy college student, or maybe you’re struggling to juggle all your responsibilities with school, work, and family. Whatever you have going on, don’t be so hard on yourself and remember that you’re doing the best you can! I’m proud of you, and SO many people around you are proud of you ❤️‍🔥. You’re truly doing great and whatever you’re struggling with will definitely pass 🥹. 

Yesterday I was practicing for my endodontics practical that we took today. It was an access preparation on a premolar (oval shape) and we had 30 minutes. I’m practicing because this is a new course, and it’s my first time exploring certain aspects of endo. It’s normal to struggle, but it’s also easy to get lost in the frustration that we aren’t good enough. This is just a friendly reminder that you ARE good enough, and you will eventually get it :) Let’s take care of ourselves and keep doing the best we can besties❤️‍🔥

little clips of my week 🤍 

This is my life as a 2nd year dental student :) this week I had a rotation in the clinic and I was able to see an extreme case for the first time. It was a really great moment where I realized again “thisss is what I’m studying for” - to improve the health of patients in the future. I was able to assist the resident and translate which made me feel really thankful I could be of service even in small ways. I think one of the best ways to rediscover your passion for dentistry if you’re in college and exhausted with DAT prep and school is through volunteering and shadowing/connecting with patients. It’s easy to get caught up in the stress of your studies and lab, but you need to remember ultimately you WILL be able to do the dentistry you’ve always dreamed of. It just takes some time to get there. Even for me, I’m not there yet but I know I eventually will be and right now is just the preparation phase so we can be fully equipped as health care professionals 🤍

Hi everyone! 

As I finish up my D2 year, I want to reflect on all the positives that have been going on in my life as well as ask myself: what does greatness mean to me?

Breast cancer awareness post 🩷

Hi guys, in the midst of midterm season I wanted to get on here and talk about breast cancer awareness month approaching! As a dental student, we don’t only learn about the mouth but about the whole body! 
If you’ve lost a loved one due to breast cancer then you know how badly you wish it would’ve been detected sooner to increase their chances of survival. 

I wanted to post some friendly reminders, stats to know, and how we can do breast cancer screenings on ourselves! 

🩷1 in 8 women in the US are diagnosed with breast cancer in their lifetime. In 2023 alone, an approximate 297,790 women will be diagnosed with invasive breast cancer. 
🩷However, early detection can make a major difference in survival rate! If caught early, the 5-year relative survival rate is 99%! 
🩷breast self-exams are easy to do! In women still menstruating, exams should be done monthly and in post-menopausal women, they should be done on the same day of every month.
🩷 to do a self-exam use light, medium, and firm pressure to feel for any new lumps, thickenings, hard knots, or any other changes. If you note any of these that weren’t there previously, alert your doctor :).

Breast cancer is more common than we would think, and it’s important to make sure we and our loved ones are being screened! 🩷

*statistics and self-exam instructions can be found on the National Breast Cancer Foundation website*

working on having balance ✨🦷

mini life update: 
D3 feels more hectic than D2!🫠 I think it’s because of having more exams, doing research this year, and seeing our own patients now. Definitely doable but I will say I’ve had to work more on my time management this year. 

But I wanted to make this post to serve as your friendly reminder to have balance (to avoid feeling burnt out in grad school)💓. 

My top tips for this:
✨find people you enjoy studying with👯‍♀️
I can’t stress this enough that studying CAN be fun if you like your setting and if you enjoy the people near you. It personally helps motivate me when I meet up with friends and we put do our work near each other. It helps me not fall behind and avoid cramming

✨Actively listen in lectures🎧
This really cuts down on time/ having to rewatch lectures if you take notes the first time. But I also like to use Notability to record the lectures so I can listen to them anywhere if I have some free time (like when I’m driving to school). If I feel I have to relisten to a lecture, I’ll do it on my drives to and from home. 

✨plan out your fun time 🎉
I try to plan something fun at the end of every week that I look forward to and I feel like it helps me get my work done. For example, I have 3 exams this week but once I get through them I can have fun on Friday. Making a schedule and giving yourself breaks really helps you recharge to come back and start fresh. 

I hope these little tips help some 💓 but my best advice is to keep going!!! For right now it may feel like you’re only surviving but soon enough you’ll be thriving ✨

the world doesn’t end with small hiccups in your journey 🫶🫶🫶. Remember everyone’s path to their career is different! 🦷

For me, I didn’t have a clear example for how to get into dentistry. The transition from high school to college was especially difficult. My first semester of college I had to withdraw from some courses and I remember worrying so much about how dental schools would feel seeing W’s on my transcript and my gap year, but in the end everything worked out perfectly. 💓

I truly believe I’m in the right place in my career, at the right time. 

If you feel behind or worry about some items on your transcript/resume, remember there are always options to improve and show you’re a well rounded applicant! There are also other parts of your application that will shine through that people will really admire so try not to get fixated on small hiccups during your journey 🦷✨
